repository of Cuban and Cuban-American materials outside of the island.&nbsp; Mrs. de Varona has worked tirelessly for more than four decades to preserve and promote Cuban and Cuban-American history and culture.&nbsp; She strives to keep the words and images of people alive in order to honor the past and guide us towards the future.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In spring 2005, the University of Miami announced the first endowed faculty chair of the University of Miami Libraries, the &ldquo;Esperanza Bravo de Varona Chair&rdquo;, named in honor of this Cuban-American librarian and archivist.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mrs. de Varona received a liberal arts education and degree in library sciences in Havana, Cuba.&nbsp; In 1965, she arrived in the United States.&nbsp; While working at the University of Miami, Mrs. de Varona received her Master&rsquo;s in Library Sciences from Florida State University.&nbsp; Mrs. de Varona&rsquo;s career at the University of Miami has spanned 40 years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mrs. de Varona served for three consecutive years as member of the UM Academic Personnel Board. &nbsp;She served as a founding member and president of the Society of Florida Archivists and was appointed as a member of the State Historical Records Advisory Board by three consecutive Florida governors. &nbsp;She chaired the Section of the University and Research Institution Archives at the International Council of Archives headquartered in Paris. &nbsp;She is a member of the Society of American Archivists and member of SALALM (Seminar on the Acquisition of Latin American Library Materials), and honorary member of the Beta Phi Mu, the International Library and Information Studies Honor Society. &nbsp;She has participated as a speaker at many national and international conferences, and is interviewed frequently by the press.<br />\r\nAmong her many honors, Mrs. de Varona has received the &quot;Floridana Award,&quot; presented by the Cuban Women&#39;s Club in Miami, Florida on September 10, 1994; &quot;Facts About Cuban Exiles (FACE)&quot; in Miami, Florida on September 7, 2000; the 2003 International Award from the <em>Asociaci&oacute;n Cultural con Cuba en la Distancia,</em> in C&aacute;diz, Spain, on May 20, 2003; the 2004 Award of Excellence from the Society of Florida Archivists; a &ldquo;Proclamation&rdquo; by Miami-Dade County Office of the Mayor and Board of County Commissioners that proclaimed Friday, May 14, 2004 as Esperanza B. de Varona Day and recipient of the &ldquo;Tributo a la Mujer Hispanic Award&rdquo; in the category of education by the magazine <u>Vanidades</u>, the world&rsquo;s leading Spanish-language women&rsquo;s lifestyle magazine on November 14, 2006.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mrs. de Varona&rsquo;s pioneering spirit has been a force in the professional archivist community.&nbsp; She was one of the first archivists certified by the Academy of Certified Archivists.&nbsp; Esperanza does not believe that the mission of collecting, preserving, and promoting history and culture is her path alone.&nbsp; Esperanza de Varona has mentored and employed women and Hispanics during her long career, and she continues to promote the preservation and dissemination of diverse cultures and histories in our community.</p>\r\n','','Professor','',227,'Essie Rodriguez','Daughter','305-262-8801','2824 Southwest 92nd Court','Miami,','FL','33165','305-221-6256','305-903-3263','305-284-4900','88','25.743142,-80.344723',0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(96,'Gomez-Rossie','Gladys ','Community Relations Coordinator','284-4008',109,0,'ggblanco@miami.edu','',0,1,NULL,1,'','{\"css\": \"basic\"}','','','Administrative Assistant','233',94,'Oscar M. Blanco, III','Son','786-229-5325','932 Southwest 136th Place','Miami,','FL','33184','305-551-8403','786-473-9809','305-284-4027','43','25.758873,-80.416482',0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(98,'Estorino Dooling','Maria','Esperanza Bravo de Varona Chair, Cuban Heritage Collection','284-4008',109,1,'mestorino@miami.edu','',0,1,'8fab3094206e39d72803d64af7ae4287',1,'talkback|faq|records|librarian|supervisor|admin_calendar','{\"css\": \"basic\"}','<p><span style=\"line-height: 1.6em;\">Follow Maria on Twitter <a href=\"https://twitter.com/mariaestorino\">@mariaestorino</a></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.6em;\">Maria R. Estorino Dooling is the Esperanza Bravo de Varona Chair of the Cuban Heritage Collection. In this role, she provides leadership for the development of the Collection as a center for scholarhip&nbsp;and its continued growth as the premier collection in the United States on Cuba and its diaspora. At the University of Miami Libraries, Maria has developed and overseen a fellowships program and&nbsp;oral history projects. &nbsp;Throughout her career, she has been a&nbsp;curatorial partner in&nbsp;various digital initiatives, including serving as the Archival Director for the Cuban Theater Digital Archive. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A Miami native, Maria joined the faculty of the University of Miami Libraries&nbsp;in 2001 as Director for a&nbsp;grant-funded digitization project. &nbsp;She then served&nbsp;as Archivist for the Cuban Heritage Collection from 2003 to 2005 and as Interim Head of Special Collections from 2005 to 2007. &nbsp;She returned to the Cuban Heritage Collection in 2007 as Deputy Chair and Chief Operations Manager and was appointed Chair in 2013.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPrior to her joining the Univeristy of Miami Libraries, Maria worked at the Northeastern University Libraries, Massachusetts Historical Society, and Blackside, Inc. She received a Master&rsquo;s of Arts in history from Northeastern University and a Master&rsquo;s of Science in Library Science from Simmons College.&nbsp; She also holds a Bachelor&rsquo;s in history from Loyola University New Orleans. &nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMaria is a member of the Society of American Archivists (SAA), in which she has served in several roles, including as an appointed member of the&nbsp;Diversity Committee and as the elected Chair of the 2011 Nominating Committee.&nbsp; She was treasurer of the Society of Florida Archivists (SFA) from 2001 to 2008 and served on the Florida State Historical Records Advisory Board from 2002 to 2004.&nbsp; Additionally, she is a member of the Seminar on the Acquisition of Latin American Library Materials (SALALM), the Association of College and Research Libraries (ACRL), and the Latin American Studies Association (LASA).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maria&#39;s professional interests include public history,&nbsp;<span style=\"font-size: 13px; line-height: 20.7999992370605px;\">the documentation of underrepresented communities, Hispanic manuscript collections in U.S. repositories, and Latinos in the archival profession</span>. &nbsp;</p>\r\n','','Librarian Associate Professor','',431,'Peter Dooling','Husband','305-479-6797','3050 Southwest 21st Street','Miami,','FL','33145','305-262-9730','305-491-3151','305-284-4027','87','25.751499,-80.2435689',42.1663,132.269,0,1.83333,1.83333,NULL),(101,'Varona','Lesbia','Professor Emeritus ','284-4900',109,0,'lovarona@miami.edu','',0,1,NULL,1,'talkback|faq|records|librarian|supervisor','{\"css\": \"basic\"}','<p>Lesbia Orta Varona has worked in research libraries since graduation from high school in Havana, Cuba. &nbsp;Pursuant to a college education with the goal of becoming a librarian, she was a staff member at the <em>Biblioteca Nacional Jos&eacute; Mart&iacute;</em>, Cuba&rsquo;s national library. &nbsp;Exiled in the United States in 1966, she immediately began working full-time at the University of Miami&rsquo;s Richter Library while completing undergraduate studies. &nbsp;A Bachelor of Arts degree from UM (1972) was followed by a Master&rsquo;s of Library Sciences from Florida State University in 1974.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Upon receiving the Master&rsquo;s degree, Lesbia became a UM Libraries faculty member with an appointment to the Periodicals and Government Publications Department. &nbsp;Promoted to Head of the Microforms and Reserves Department, a position she held for ten years, she supervised the Cuban Reserves &ndash; the collection of all UM non-archival holdings on Cuba. &nbsp;She also became the bibliographer for Latin America, Spain, and Portugal during that time, an appointment she has continued to hold after UM Libraries implemented plans to create a unique collection to include the Cuban materials from both Special Collections and the former Cuban Reserves. &nbsp;Thus, Lesbia Varona became the first reference librarian and bibliographer for the <em>Cuban Heritage Collection</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mrs. Varona is an active member of the International Seminar on the Acquisition of Latin American Library Materials (SALALM), having chaired the Subcommittee on Cuban Bibliography several times. &nbsp;She is also a recognized participant in the cultural life of South Florida, having supported Hispanic theatre initiatives for nearly four decades.</p>\r\n','','Librarian Associate Professor','',98,'Orlando Varona','Husband','305-261-9683','7600 Southwest 19th Street','Miami,','FL','33155','305-261-9683','305-632-3781','305-284-4900','89','25.752692,-80.31791',0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(104,'Gowing','Cheryl','Associate Dean, Library Information Systems &amp; Access','284-6018',126,1,'cgowing@miami.edu','',0,1,'f16a74f6c71f84a06622903170dc7920',1,'talkback|faq|records|eresource_mgr|videos|admin|librarian|supervisor|view_map|admin_calendar','{\"css\": \"basic\"}','<p>Cheryl Gowing has served as a member of the librarian faculty since 1987.&nbsp;&nbsp; In her current position as Director of Information Management &amp; Systems, she provides leadership and oversight for the&nbsp; Access Services, Cataloging &amp; Metadata Services, Systems Support, and&nbsp; Web &amp; Emerging Technologies Departments.&nbsp;&nbsp; These departments are responsible for the access &amp; circulation of all library materials, interlibrary loan services,&nbsp; the cataloging, maintenance, and metadata descriptions for all library materials and digital collections, the maintenance of all hardware and software employed within the Libraries, design and maintenance of all library web pages, and the maintenance of the Libraries&rsquo; automation system, including the library catalog.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms. Gowing received a Bachelor&rsquo;s in Music from Rhode Island College, her Masters in Library Science in 1985 and a Masters in Music in 1984 in Organ and Liturgical Music both from the University of Michigan. Her previous positions at the University include Music Cataloger, Head of Cataloging, Integrated Library Systems Coordinator, and Director of Technical &amp; Access Services.&nbsp; Prior to joining the University of Miami faculty in 1987, she was a music cataloger for an NEH grant at the Bowling Green State University Popular Music Sound Recording Archives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms. Gowing currently serves on the University&#39;s Academic Computing Advisory Committee and the Information Technology Leadership Council.&nbsp; She has represented the Libraries on the Faculty Senate and General Welfare Committees, the Senate Women &amp; Minorities Committee, the Senate Library &amp; Information Technology Committee, the Portal Steering Committee, and the Provost&rsquo;s Women&rsquo;s Advisory Committee on Academic Affairs.&nbsp;&nbsp; She was elected Vice-Chair/Chair-Elect in 2004 to a three year term on the Innovative Users Group Steering Committee, serving as Chair in 2005-2006.&nbsp; She is active within several library professional organizations, including LITA [Library Information Technology Association]. ALCTS [Association of Library Collections &amp; Technical Services], ACRL [Association of College &amp; Research Libraries], and FLA [Florida Library Association].&nbsp; Ms. Gowing is also in her second elected term as President of the Library Board of Trustees for the Miami Shores Brockway Memorial Library.</p>\r\n','','Librarian Associate Professor','301Q',431,'Michael Stock','Husband','(work)305-995-2220 (cell)305-3439376','268 Northeast 102nd Street','Miami Shores,','FL','33138','305-757-5216','305-505-2898','305-284-4027','46','25.868589,-80.192184',29.6529,139.498,0,1.83333,1.83333,NULL),(105,'Grant','Courtnay','Systems Service Administrator','284-5465',126,0,'cgrant@miami.edu','',0,1,'27e84c700c62f7c1181a82f5e8d531ff',1,'talkback|faq|records|eresource_mgr|videos|admin|admin_calendar','{\"css\": \"basic\"}','','','Systems Administrator','',104,'Ryan Grant','Father','305-248-5548','27201 Southwest 167th Avenue','Homestead,','FL','33032','305-248-5548','786-863-3799','305-284-4027','94','25.513627,-80.461071',18.9898,134.332,2,1.83333,1.83333,NULL),(108,'Robar','Terri','Education &amp; Outreach Librarian ','284-6028',118,0,'trobar@miami.edu','',0,1,'80241d24e4997e2047145d21b957c28f',1,'talkback|faq|records|librarian|admin_calendar','{\"css\": \"basic\"}','<p>Terri Robar joined the faculty of the University Libraries in 1983.&nbsp; She received her Master&rsquo;s of Library Science from Ball State University.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She has worked as the Maps and Special Formats Librarian since 1998.&nbsp; She provides service and cataloging for the General Map Collection. &nbsp;In addition, she serves as liaison to the departments of Philosophy and Geography and Regional Studies.&nbsp; She also selects materials for the video and audio book collections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms. Robar is a member of the North American Cartographic Information Society.</p>\r\n','','Geography, Communications, Maps, and Audiovisual Librarian','347I',352,'Betty Moyer','Sister','602-595-7677','11605 Southwest 90th Terrace','Miami,','FL','33176','305-412-2290','305-484-4988','305-284-4027','','25.683886,-80.382349',30.923,115.163,0,1.83333,1.83333,NULL),(115,'Beynon','Loretta','Interlibrary Loan Lending Assistant','284-6102',113,0,'lbeynon@miami.edu','',0,1,NULL,1,'','{\"css\": \"basic\"}','','','Library Assistant','',233,'Camila Cochrane','Friend','305-856-5080','7865 Camino Real, Apartment #L-403','Miami,','FL',